{
  "stem": "935.5",
  "chunk_idx": 7,
  "model": "openai/gpt-oss-120b",
  "elapsed_s": 2.5,
  "sentences_input": [
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 37,
      "text": "And outside stood Margit-- my non-Jewish friend from Amsterdam, waving papers.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 38,
      "text": "On my life, as true as I'm sitting here-- Silvia, Silvia, I've got your papers, I've got your papers from Budapest, from your father.",
      "word_count": 24
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 39,
      "text": "She tried to get in, and of course, no such luck.",
      "word_count": 11
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 40,
      "text": "They kept her back.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 41,
      "text": "But then Meier, this was the name of this non-Jewish go-between-- took me to his room, and he explained what had had happened.",
      "word_count": 23
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 42,
      "text": "Margit had come-- Margit-- the papers arrived three days after I had left Amsterdam.",
      "word_count": 14
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 43,
      "text": "With my Hungarian father, papers from the Hungarian president, from the Nazis, from the German, all totally legal.",
      "word_count": 18
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 44,
      "text": "Illegal but legal.",
      "word_count": 3
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 45,
      "text": "And Margit tried to get permission to travel, to bring them to me.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 46,
      "text": "Of course, she didn't get permission.",
      "word_count": 6
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 47,
      "text": "So she went also illegal.",
      "word_count": 5
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 48,
      "text": "Got arrested at the border, slipped herself through with a couple of German soldiers, who brought her to me, to Belgium.",
      "word_count": 21
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 49,
      "text": "And she thought they would really release me.",
      "word_count": 8
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 50,
      "text": "She would get to the kommandant, and give him the papers, and say, you've got to let her go.",
      "word_count": 19
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 51,
      "text": "She doesn't belong here.",
      "word_count": 4
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 52,
      "text": "She didn't manage to do so, because the kommandant refused to see her.",
      "word_count": 13
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 53,
      "text": "So the only thing she got to do is she let me know that she was going to Brussels to see the big, big, big Nazi from the Belgian thing, by the name of Erdman, E-R-D-M-A-N, to get him the papers to see that I'd be released.",
      "word_count": 47
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 54,
      "text": "And she left.",
      "word_count": 3
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 55,
      "text": "And I got a card from her, from Brussels, that the man she wanted to see was on his way to Berlin, but she handed it to someone else, whatever.",
      "word_count": 30
    },
    {
      "segment_idx": 14,
      "sentence_idx_in_seg": 56,
      "text": "And I was reading the card outside, on the staircase, with two of my friends-- three, actually.",
      "word_count": 17
    }
  ],
